{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 PURGATORIO CANTO 10}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-6.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The opening verses of the canto tell us that Dante is obeying the angel's warning \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.132) not to look back (in this potentially resembling one of the disciples of Jesus even \softline
more than Lot's wife or Orpheus -- see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.131-132) and that the gate of \softline
purgatory makes such noise because it is so infrequently opened, since most human beings prefer \softline
to pretend that their crooked way is straight and spend eternity in hell as a result.  This last image \softline
will be reinforced immediately by the undulating path through the rock that the travelers must \softline
follow, reminiscent of the sinful life they have left behind, and eventually, as Singleton points out \softline
(comm. to verse 3), by the misconception that what is in fact crooked is straight in Dante's dream \softline
of the Siren (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.7-15).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Poletto's commentary (1894) to this passage reminds the reader of the total contrast \softline
between the solitary state of Dante and his guide, both when they approached the angelic warder \softline
and now, having proceeded farther up the mountain (see verse 21), and the vast crowds of \softline
damned sinners found both inside the gate of hell and before Minos in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.119-120 and \softline
V.12.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab On the question of the relationship between the protagonist here and Orpheus, Lot's wife, \softline
and/or one of Jesus's disciples, the commentary tradition is particularly various.  Of those who \softline
claim the relevance of one relationship or another (some two dozen), almost all do so in their \softline
glosses to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.132, while only three do so here.  More cite the Bible, especially Luke \softline
9:62, than anything else, with the reference to Lot's wife, whether in Genesis (19:26) or in Luke \softline
(17:32), somewhat less present, and that to Orpheus least.  It is curious that Pietro di Dante in his \softline
comment to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX (Pietro1, to vv. 131-132) cites only the first passage in Luke, Jesus's \softline
words to his disciples, while in his comment to this passage he refers only to Lot and Orpheus.  \softline
Similarly inconsistent, Fallani (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.131-132) at first refers to all three; when he \softline
reaches this passage (comm. to vv. 5-6) he has decided that the reference is to Luke, specifically \softline
rejecting Orpheus (and not even mentioning Lot).  It is clear that all three references fit the \softline
context, but it is probably also true, as Fallani evidently realized, that the passage in Luke fits \softline
better than the others, for at least two reasons.  Dante is uniquely referred to here because he, as a \softline
still-mortal being, alone can be ejected from purgatory for improper behavior and denied his \softline
forward trajectory into a very special fellowship, while Orpheus wants to return to his past in the \softline
present, a quite different ambition.  Lot only seems to fit as well as Jesus's putative disciple, since \softline
he is told by God to head for the mountains to escape destruction (Genesis 19:17-26), but \softline
successfully wheedles his Lord into letting him move from Sodom to Zoar instead (apparently \softline
preferring the suburbs to rural isolation), and it is only once Lot is safely inside the new city that \softline
his wife, hanging back, is caught in the firestorm that destroyed the cities of the plain.  That \softline
context does not fit as well as does that of the first passage in Luke, as neither Lot nor his wife \softline
seems much interested in the genuinely new life that God's mountain betokened.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-16.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As opposed to the wide and easy entrance to hell (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.20), that to purgatory is \softline
narrow and difficult.  For the reference to the 'needle's eye' [verse 16]), see Christ's words to the \softline
disciples (Matthew 19:24): 'And further I say to you, it is easier for a camel to pass through the \softline
eye of a needle, than for a rich man to enter the kingdom of heaven.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Virgil insists on the need for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 arte}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , or skill in navigating a tight spot, apparently so as not to \softline
allow Dante to be wounded by the sharp edges of the rock's outcroppings, and thus in not 
following the shortest path along this labyrinthine passageway, but the one that moves back and \softline
forth from the farther wall in order to avoid the protuberances on the nearer.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab His reference to the waning moon (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XX.127, where we learn the moon was full on \softline
Thursday night) portrays the dark crescent in that body as leading it toward the horizon as it sets.  \softline
It is now Monday morning; the moon was full 3.5 days ago and set in the western sky exactly at \softline
sunrise.  With four days of retardation, 50 minutes per day, it is now setting approximately three \softline
hours and twenty minutes after sunrise.  Since Dante awoke before the gate just after 8am (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
IX.44), it is perhaps slightly more than an hour later.  In that time he has been admitted by the \softline
warder and made his way with Virgil through the 'eye of the needle.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This verse distances Virgil from Dante by insisting on his freedom from the body's \softline
weight and yet equates the two travelers as being equally uninformed as to their impending \softline
choices.  We have known that Virgil is not proficient in the ways of purgatory from the outset \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.61-63); now that we are in true purgatory the point is underlined.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-23.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   See Tobia Toscano ("Canto X," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Neapolitana: "Purgatorio,"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ed. \softline
Pompeo Giannantonio [Naples: Loffredo, 1989]), pp. 207-8, on two debates among the \softline
commentators: Does this wall make a right or an obtuse angle with the smooth pavement?  Do the \softline
penitents observe what is sculpted on the wall or not?  Toscano strongly supports the notion that \softline
the wall is set at an obtuse angle so that the penitents are able to see what is depicted on it.  If this \softline
were not the case, he continues, God's art would be wasted on them, unable to move their heads \softline
high enough to see the instructive decoration, which would, without their observation, be mere \softline
ornament.  If the terraces are cut into the side of the mountain and if this verse, as many \softline
commentators believe, indicates that the inner bank of every terrace is part of the tapered shape of \softline
the mountain as a whole, then Toscano is correct.  However, should we ever be forced to decide \softline
that, as Pietrobono (1946), Mattalia (1960), and Vazzana ({\u8220\'93}Il Canto X del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Nuove \softline
letture dantesche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. IV [Florence: Le Monnier, 1970], pp. 65-67) believe, this terrace (and \softline
every other one?) has a perpendicular wall as its inner border, we would also probably deduce \softline
that, in God's realm, even stiff-necked penitents will somehow be able to see all of the sculpting \softline
that is put there for their instruction.  (Dante's illustrators are not much help in this respect; if one \softline
examines the two illustrations of the purgatorial mount found in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Encyclopedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [ed. R. \softline
Lansing, New York: Garland, 2000], pp. 725 and 729, one finds that one shows the first \softline
condition, the other, the second.)  Since Dante never clarified this point and since the manuscript \softline
tradition of the line (verse 30) crucial to its interpretation itself has caused much uncertainty, we \softline
really cannot say what the meaning is.  Bosco/Reggio (1979) contrive a compromise: the lower \softline
part of the wall is slanted, but the rest of it is perpendicular.  This might solve certain problems, \softline
but cannot be supported by the text.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For some of the problems associated with this verse see the note to vv. 22-23.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1   \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Art is clearly a major theme of this canto.  We hear now of the aesthetic \softline
superiority of God's intaglios over the work of the sculptor Polycletus or the creative genius of \softline
nature herself.  At verse 97 we learn, not of Dante's instruction, but of his delight in the intaglios.  \softline
Near the canto's close we are told in a simile of the genuine distress that can be caused by our \softline
looking at a sculpted figure of a crunched human shape in a corbel (vv. 131-134).  All these 
aesthetic moments have at their root the experience of art as moving its audience by its mimetic \softline
capacity.  The morality of the art found on this terrace is not to be doubted, but in this canto (as \softline
opposed to the next) we at first find art treasured for purely aesthetic reasons (but see the note to \softline
vv. 97-99).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The words that make their way through the three descriptions of intaglios in vv. 31-81 \softline
insist on the artistic nature of what the protagonist sees: forms of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 intaglio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : 32, 38, 55; of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 imagine}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : \softline
39, 41, 62; of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 storia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : 52, 71, 73.  This art of God, which some commentators have looked upon as \softline
uncannily predicting the eventual sculpture of Michelangelo, may be more advanced than that of \softline
mere mortals, and even of nature, but it somehow does not seem very far removed from that of \softline
Dante himself.  See Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Poets}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1984]), p. \softline
275: 'The exaltation of divine art at the expense of human art paradoxically leads to the exaltation \softline
of that human artist who most closely imitates divine art, who writes a poem to which heaven and \softline
earth contribute, and who by way of being only a scribe becomes the greatest of poets.'  Mazzotta \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante, Poet of the Desert}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1979], pp. 237-52) frames his \softline
discussion of this canto in Dante's supposed 'ambiguity' about the value of fame.  For a spirited \softline
and dubious reply to Mazzotta's compulsion to find 'ambiguity' nearly everywhere in Dante's work \softline
and as the hallmark of his way of thinking and writing, see Mastrobuono (review article of \softline
Mazzotta{\u8219\'27}s book), "Criticism on Ambiguity,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Italian Culture}{\plain \fs24 \f1  5 (1984), pointing out, by listing the \softline
over-abundance of assertions of this view (pp. 16-17), its tendency to distort the problem it \softline
examines.  One might also wonder why in his monograph Mazzotta never even discusses Dante's \softline
own early statement that at least certain elements of poems can be understood plainly because \softline
their authors know what they mean when they resort to rhetorical figures which they are fully \softline
capable of explaining clearly (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXV.10).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Polycletus, Athenian sculptor of the fifth century B.C., for Dante represented the height of \softline
classical Greek art.  Torraca (1905), in his gloss to vv. 32-33, points out that previous thirteenth-century Italian writers cited him in a similar way.  Sources of information about him were found in \softline
Cicero, Quintilian, and Pliny.  And Aristotle, mentioning him in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Nichomachean Ethics}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
brought him to the attention of St. Thomas.  And so, even if Italian vernacular writers of this \softline
period had never seen his work, they could refer to it as Dante does here. Benvenuto (comm. to \softline
vv. 28-33) tells the interesting tale that he, in a private house in Florence, saw a marble statue of \softline
naked Venus that was supposed to have been done by Polycletus, but says that he does not \softline
believe it actually was, since, on the (erroneous) authority of Pliny, Polycletus worked in bronze, \softline
not in marble.  He adds that Dante really should have named Praxiteles here.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The first example of each virtue (here Humility), opposed to the capital vice \softline
purged on each of the seven terraces, is always Mary.  These four tercets are spare and central in \softline
their presentation of the Annunciation: only Gabriel and Mary are seen, minus the 'background' \softline
expected by any medieval reader, familiar with the iconography of this moment: dove, ray of light, \softline
garden, etc.  As the Ottimo (comm. to vv. 34-44) has it, the 'long-standing ban' had been in effect \softline
since the time recorded in Genesis 3 (the Fall) and was only rescinded when Christ harrowed hell.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The sculpted forms are so vivid that they actually seem to speak.  Thus does Dante recast \softline
the key spoken moments of Luke 1:26-38, Gabriel's charge and Mary's humble acceptance of it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab As for a tradition of renditions of 'visible speech' in painting see Fengler and Stephany \softline
("The Visual Arts: A Basis for Dante's Imagery in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradise}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Michigan \softline
Academician}{\plain \fs24 \f1  10 [1977]), p. 132: Simone Martini's Uffizi }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Annunciation}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (1333 -- but reflecting a 
pre-existent tradition), where the angel's words are depicted on a horizontal line on the painting's \softline
gold background.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-54.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Bosco/Reggio (comm. to vv. 22-54) make explicit what is almost said by many of \softline
those commentators who deal with the phrase in verse 53, 'varcai Virgilio' (I went past Virgil): it \softline
is a fine, realistic detail with no further significance.  Yet this entire passage, in which Virgil gets \softline
Dante to stop enjoying so deeply the representation of Gabriel and Mary and to make himself \softline
available to more of God's art, has certain overtones that might cast a different light on the \softline
relationship between the two poets here.  The Annunciation was nearly, we might reflect, the \softline
subject of Virgil's fourth }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Eclogue}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , the child to be born to a virgin that, had he only known which \softline
child and which virgin, might have saved him.  It is this scene from which Virgil, in all innocence, \softline
pulls Dante away.  And, while what follows merely describes Dante's moving past Virgil, who had \softline
been standing between him and the first intaglio, from left to right, so as better to inspect the next \softline
work, it also describes physically what has a moral status, that is, Dante surpasses Virgil as an \softline
artist because he is more available to the meaning of God's art.  In this vein see Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's \softline
Poets}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1984]), p. 278.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 55-69.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  has readied us to observe, Dante will now couple his subordinate \softline
exemplary figures as scriptural and classical, more specifically Old Testament and Roman.  This \softline
passage consolidates key elements of the narrative concerning David's bringing the Ark of the \softline
Covenant into Jerusalem: his dancing before it, his wife Michal's scorn, and her resultant \softline
barrenness (II Samuel 6:1-23).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 56-57.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Uzzah's presumption in attempting to assist Him who requires no help of any kind \softline
is related in II Samuel 6:6-7: he tried to steady the Ark when the movement of the oxen seemed \softline
about to topple it; for this God strikes him down immediately, killing him for his prideful \softline
insistence on a mission not enjoined.  For Dante's complex and amusing acknowledgment, both \softline
here and, more specifically, in his eleventh }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that he is, in some ways, the 'new Uzzah,' see \softline
Teodolinda Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Undivine "Comedy": Detheologizing Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton \softline
University Press, 1992]), p. 132, and Hollander ("Dante as Uzzah? [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X 57 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XI 9-12]," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Sotto il segno di Dante: Scritti in onore di Francesco Mazzoni}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. L. Coglievina & D. \softline
De Robertis [Florence: Le Lettere, 1999], pp. 143-51).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 60-63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist's ears assure him that the seven choirs in this panel are not \softline
singing, yet his eyes insist that they are.  Just so his nose smells no perfume of incense, while his \softline
eyes can }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 see}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that the smoke indeed has an aroma.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 65.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Perhaps no passage in a poem that refers to David more than to any other personage \softline
from the Old Testament (see Hollander, "Dante's Use of the Fiftieth Psalm," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  91 \softline
[1973], pp. 145-50) is more compelling in establishing the 'figural relationship' between the two \softline
poets.  Dante, too, is a 'humble psalmist,' David's modern counterpart.  It seems just to say that no \softline
one has developed this observation as well as has Barolini (see especially }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Poets}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1984], pp. 275-78).  In 1837 Tommaseo (comm. to vv. \softline
64-66) had dealt with this scene as a metaphor for great Dante's low vernacular poetry performed \softline
beneath the scornful gaze of pedantry: 'But Dante is more than poet in certain respects, because 
he does not fear to appear less than poet and dances with his robe hitched up; but princess Michal \softline
-- I might call her "pedantry" -- sniffs from the window.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Singleton, in his commentary to verse 75, cites a passage from Gregory the Great's \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Moralia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  for David's humility: 'What is thought by others of his doings, I know not; I am more \softline
[amazed] at David dancing, than fighting.  For by fighting he subdued his enemies; but by dancing \softline
before the Lord he overcame himself.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 67-69.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Where David, down among the common people and dancing without kingly \softline
dignity, reflects the low comedic world, Michal, high above the crowd and separate from it, \softline
scornful, seems to represent the lofty, 'tragic,' or noble view.  David here serves as a forerunner \softline
for Jesus, who will identify himself with humility, while Michal seems to be associated with all \softline
those who resist humility in the name of pride.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 73-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The longest of these three scenes concerns Trajan, emperor of Rome in the years \softline
98-117.  Of those whom Dante depicts as being saved to whom all or most Christians would \softline
deny, or at least question, that status (Cato [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.75], Statius [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII.73], Trajan [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XX.44], and Ripheus [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XX.68]), only for Trajan does there exist a tradition that considered \softline
him saved.  This result of St. Gregory's prayers is even allowed as possible by St. Thomas, in what \softline
seems an unusually latitudinarian gesture, recorded in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Summa theologica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (as was perhaps first \softline
noted by Lombardi [1791], comm. to vv. 74-75): }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ST}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III, Suppl., quaest. 71, art. 5, obj. 5 [for the \softline
text in English see Singleton's note to verse 75]).  That what seems to modern ears an \softline
unbelievable story should have had the support of so rigorous a thinker as Thomas still astounds \softline
readers.  Yet, if one looks closely, one sees that Thomas does hedge his bet: Trajan's salvation by \softline
Gregory's intervention is 'probable' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 potest probabiliter aestimari}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ); further, according to Thomas, \softline
'as others say' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 secundum quosdam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), Trajan may have only had his punishment put back until \softline
Judgment Day.  Dante betrays no such hesitation: the salvation of Trajan is Gregory's 'great \softline
victory' (verse 75).  Dante is in an enviable position, both possessing Thomas's support and being \softline
able to outdo him in enthusiasm.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For some of the many medieval texts that support the miraculous salvation of Trajan and \softline
for an array of possible sources for the dialogue between Trajan and the widow, including Trajan's \softline
column in Rome, see Nancy Vickers, "Seeing is Believing: Gregory, Trajan, and Dante's Art,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  \softline
Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  101 (1983), pp. 70-72, 75-79. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For Dante's reliance on two back-to-back parables in Luke (Luke 18:1-8; 18:9-14) see \softline
Vickers, pp. 73-75.  Lombardi (comm. to verse 32) was perhaps the first to apply Luke 18:14 \softline
('qui se exaltat humiliabitur, et qui se humiliat exaltabitur' [for every one that exalts himself shall \softline
be abased; and he that humbles himself shall be exalted]) to this scene.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 73.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For the term }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 stor{\f3 \'56}ata}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Singleton (comm. to vv. 49-52): 'a depiction in art, even as \softline
stained-glass windows or initial letters in manuscripts or frescoed walls were said to be \softline
"historiated"' with historical or legendary material.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 75.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Saint Gregory, known as Gregory the Great, was pope from 590 to 604.  His lengthy \softline
commentary on the Book of Job (the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Moralia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), one of the most influential writings of the earlier \softline
middle ages, offers a different and happier understanding of Job's story than is prevalent today, \softline
insisting that it has a truly 'comic' resolution, rebinding Job to God and restoring his family.  Dante 
mentions Gregory twice, here and in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XX.106-117, in connection with the salvation of \softline
Trajan, and he is referred to in the last sphere of the heavens as one of the saved (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXVIII.133), despite the fact that he had made small errors in listing the orders of the angelic \softline
hierarchy (as had Dante himself in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.v.6) in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Moralia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For information about which popes are saved and which are damned according to the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VII.46-48.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 76.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Having been told of Gregory's 'great victory,' we are now told in what it consisted: \softline
the pope has saved a (dead) pagan emperor.  The way the text is handled reminds us of Dante's \softline
continuing hostility to the Church's insistence on the hierocrat position, in which the emperor is \softline
seen as totally dependent upon the Church for his authority.  Gregory's intervention for a great \softline
Roman emperor has, in Dante's eyes, a different style and sets a better standard.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 77-81.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The rapid strokes that fill in the details of this intaglio show that Dante is fully \softline
capable of producing the scene in pictures.  But in the following dozen verses, pushing the limits \softline
of the art he attributes to God, but which he has invented, he reports only the 'visible speech' \softline
wrought by what he saw, that is, the words induced by the carving rather than the carving itself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 82-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The exchange between the widow and Trajan, a sort of polite }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 tenzone}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , involves six \softline
speeches.  The widow seeks, Trajan denies; she seeks again and is again denied; she appeals to \softline
Trajan's moral character and he accedes, touched in those two treasured Roman inner qualities, \softline
respect for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 iustitia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 pietas}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  Francesco da Buti (comm. to vv. 28-45) was of the opinion that, \softline
just as those who are prideful are so against their superiors, their equals, or their inferiors, so \softline
those who are humble may be so in the same relationships.  Thus Mary is humble before her \softline
superior, God; David before his equals, the priests; and Trajan before his inferior, the widow.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-96.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   What is new to Dante is not so to God (but this does not reduce the novelty or the \softline
excitement of it for Dante [see verse 104] or for us).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, \softline
1969]), pp. 297-300, points out that this passage, with its 'speech made visible,' connects with two \softline
other similar moments in the poem, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.1-9 (the writing over the gate of hell) and \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XVIII.91-93 (the 'skywriting' in the heaven of Jupiter), and suggests that all of them \softline
may be thought of as representing 'visible speech,' as was suggested by one of his students, \softline
Gregory Curfman (Princeton '68).  Curfman also suggested that each passage was further related \softline
by containing a focal word, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 giustizia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.4; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.93; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVIII.91--now in Latin, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 iustitiam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) and then still further by involving Trajan.  This formulation works easily for the last two \softline
passages, but requires a contorted argument (along a path that travels through Hezekiah and \softline
Roman triumphal arches) to attach Trajan to the gate of hell.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Mestica was perhaps the first commentator to apply widely and frequently his perception \softline
of the significance of the term }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 visibile parlare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  for Dante's art (as compared with Virgil's) \softline
throughout the poem, beginning with the description of Charon in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.82-99: 'Comparing \softline
Charon as portrayed by Virgil and Dante quickly reveals the remarkable artistry used by the pupil \softline
when he imitated his teacher, as well as the originality and power of his style.  Virgil paints \softline
descriptively, employing ample displays of images and colors; Dante sculpts, using speech made \softline
visible.'  Mestica deploys the phrase fourteen more times in his commentary as he marvels at the 
power of Dante's art.\par
