University of Chicago Press, 1993], pp. 37-45).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 97-99.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   These images of humility reflect the pattern that we will find on each terrace: first \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 exempla}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of the virtue that directly opposes the vice repented (here humility and pride), ultimately \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 exempla}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of the vice itself (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.25-63).  Thus the penitents are at first encouraged and \softline
finally warned lest they backslide.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 100-102.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's delectation has delayed the travelers long enough so that even this slow-moving band of penitents, coming along behind them, can become visible to Virgil (but not to the \softline
art-absorbed Dante), even though the path was totally bare when the two poets arrived on it (vv. \softline
25-26).  It is a curious fact of this art-filled canto that, of the two poets, Virgil has clearly the \softline
shortest attention span to give to art.  He feels he has to urge Dante to take his eyes off Gabriel \softline
and Mary (verse 46) in order to examine David, and now interrupts Dante's delectation in the \softline
images of Trajan and the widow in order to get him to look at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 real}{\plain \fs24 \f1  souls.  (He is obviously \softline
himself not nearly so absorbed by God's art.)  It is a bit difficult to know what to make of these \softline
moments.  Virgil resembles the less art-responsive member of a couple in a museum, waiting for \softline
his friend, totally absorbed, to finish looking so that their tour may continue.  Further, the word \softline
used to describe Virgil's distracting locution is }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mormorava}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (murmured).  Dante uses it seven other \softline
times in the poem (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.86, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIV.37, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIV.47, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXII.37, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XX.19, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XX.26, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXV.21), and it usually denotes some form of less-than-clear speech, \softline
uttered in this way because the speaker is in pain or distracted (in the only preceding occurrence, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.86, it is the riven, speaking flame of Ulysses that murmurs).  For Dante to put together \softline
the very word that for him most stands for eloquence, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 poeta}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , with 'murmured' is striking. The \softline
commentators are mainly silent in response to Virgil's murmuring.  Benvenuto (comm. to verse \softline
101), the only one before the twentieth century to pay the word significant notice, says this: \softline
Seeing Dante so rapt in aesthetic pleasure, Virgil interrupts him smilingly in a low voice to \softline
indicate that now his pupil can observe some }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 real}{\plain \fs24 \f1  purgation (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 aliam purgationem veram}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  Torraca \softline
(comm. to verse 101) tries a different tack: Virgil murmurs because he is puzzled by the nature of \softline
these new things moving toward him.  Trucchi (comm. to verse 101) and Pietrobono (comm. to \softline
verse 101) suggest that the words are said by Virgil half to himself because he is absorbed in what \softline
he is seeing and afflicted by the problem of how to proceed in his guidance.  The last seems a \softline
reasonable explanation.  Yet no one has, with the exception of Vickers, paid attention to the \softline
curious and disturbing notion that Virgil, of all people, should murmur.  Here is her formulation, \softline
in partial response to that word: 'The placing of Virgil face to face with divine assurance of the \softline
salvation of Trajan, a man of no more faith than he, cannot but emphasize the enigma of Virgil's \softline
situation' (Nancy Vickers, "Seeing is Believing: Gregory, Trajan, and Dante's Art,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
101 [1983], p. 72).  She goes on to speculate that the salvation of Trajan by intervention of \softline
Gregory inevitably brings to mind another great medieval legend, that of St. Paul praying for the \softline
soul of Virgil at his tomb near Naples, a potential intervention on behalf of damned Virgil that, as \softline
far as everyone who has dealt with it is concerned, failed.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 103-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Vickers ("Seeing is Believing: Gregory, Trajan, and Dante's Art,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
101 [1983]), pp. 80-81, discusses Benvenuto's connecting the historiated walls of Carthage, with \softline
their account of the fall of Troy in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.453-495, and this scene, and then goes on to suggest \softline
that 'Aeneas is rapt in the esthetic experience and weeps; Dante the pilgrim is rapt and delights.  \softline
The one reads defeat (emptiness); the other triumphs (fullness).' \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 106-111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's third address to us, his readers, is an appeal that we accept the necessity \softline
of treatment for our ills before we are eventually free of them.  Since the 'punishments' of the \softline
saved do not seem, at first blush, all that much more pleasant than the pains of the damned, the \softline
poet wishes to emphasize the great gulf that separates them: those in hell are eternal; these here \softline
are timebound and will cease at least by the Day of Judgment.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112-120.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This passage has caused much discussion but is in fact not as difficult as it has \softline
been made to seem.  The purpose of the entire passage is to get Dante to understand that what he \softline
is looking at is human and not merely a procession of mobile rocks.  Virgil says he, too, had \softline
trouble making this fact out at first, but eventually could see that there were beings moving \softline
beneath the rocks.  A single gesture makes this clear: they beat their breasts.  And it is a gesture \softline
that accords with the penitential feelings of the penitent prideful, as Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Scripture and Classical Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1969 (1896)]), p. 49, \softline
clearly pointed out, citing Luke 18:13, where the publican beats his breast in humility.  \softline
Nonetheless, Ignazio Baldelli ("L'angariatissimo 'si picchia' / 'si nicchia' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ., X 120]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Filologia \softline
e critica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  15 [1990]), pp. 480-84, argues, against Petrocchi, for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 si nicchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (and not }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 si picchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  \softline
While he does not follow the path of those who argue for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 nicchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as meaning 'lament' (a meaning \softline
that is found in the appearance of that verb in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVIII.103) which, as Petrocchi says, is not a \softline
probable reading given that one is less likely to see than to hear lamentation, he does argue for the \softline
somewhat more recondite meaning of the verb, 'hides itself,' 'settles in its niche,' 'is in its nest,' etc.  \softline
While Baldelli's negative arguments against Petrocchi and others are sound, they are not \softline
eventually convincing because the action of the verb is too confining and slight to describe what \softline
we see, souls crushed down under the heavy weight of stone.  And thus the traditional reading, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 si \softline
picchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , i.e., beating themselves on their breasts, seems still the best.  Chiavacci Leonardi \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio, con il commento di A. M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Milan: Mondadori, 1994]), p. 310, suggests that it \softline
would be difficult to carry out this self-inflicted punishment beneath the heavy rocks and wants to \softline
return to the minority view found in Jacopo della Lana, namely, that these sinners are being \softline
beaten, castigated, by God.  Torraca (comm. to vv. 118-120) had already argued that, with their \softline
knees already pushed up against their chests, they would not have space to beat into (but this is \softline
said of the similetic figure of the man on a corbel, not of the penitents) and that they would have \softline
had to use their hands and arms to steady the weights upon their backs (but Dante never tells us \softline
that this is so; again, the nature of the place allows for phenomena that may not occur in the 'real \softline
world').  Just as it does not make sense to argue about whether or not the penitent prideful can \softline
see the exemplary figures displayed upon the mountain's side from under their stones if the wall on \softline
which these figures are shown is at right angles (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.23), it does not make \softline
sense here to argue that their arms and hands are not free to pummel their chests, as the poem is a \softline
poem and this space in it, like the entire mountain above the portal in the ninth canto, is a magic \softline
mountain, without always observing natural physical laws.  Thus the souls can see what needs to \softline
be seen and pummel themselves at will.  There is a useful summary of these arguments up to the 
twentieth century in Scartazzini (comm. to verse 120).  He argues forcefully for this reading.  \softline
Further confirmation comes from the likely citation of Luke (Luke 18:13), where the publican \softline
beats his breast, a text that has solid connections to this scene (see the last paragraph of the note \softline
to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.73-93).  Michele Barbi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Problemi di critica dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Sansoni, 1934], pp. \softline
224-225) is on this side of the argument.  Further, Dante spends (and with any other hypothesis, \softline
wastes) five verses (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.115-119) having Virgil say how hard it is to make out this gesture \softline
but that, once you disentangle their bodies from the stones, you will see that they are human and \softline
not things.  Thus simple analysis of the content of the verses probably should have long ago \softline
disbarred any hypothesis that did not show how the human sign offered by the souls identified \softline
them as human.  The only hypothesis that meets this criterion is the most popular one, which also \softline
has iconography on its side.  See Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Scripture and Classical \softline
Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1969 (1896)]), p. 49.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 121-129.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The poet's second apostrophe of the canto (see vv. 106-111 for the first) is not, \softline
strictly speaking, an address to the reader but rather a castigation of all those Christians (and thus, \softline
one would expect, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 not}{\plain \fs24 \f1  all his readers) who have turned away from God.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab One of the most celebrated metaphors of the poem, the 'angelic butterfly' that each of us \softline
has as a potential destiny, is what most of us will not become.  Hugh Shankland ("Dante 'Aliger,'" \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Modern Language Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  70 [1975], pp. 764-85) suggests a relationship between Dante's name \softline
and the Latin word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 aliger}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (a Virgilian coinage, according to him, as a poetic alternative for \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alatus}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ), first used (at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.663) for Cupid, then again (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.249) for the 'winged flock' of \softline
waterfowl sent scrambling by Jove's golden eagle.  Guglielmo Gorni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lettera nome numero: \softline
L'ordine delle cose in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Bologna: Il Mulino, 1990]), pp. 185-86, makes a similar \softline
