}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 128.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   While God wills that we, caterpillars that we are, become butterflies, Heaven-bound \softline
souls, we choose to be even less than those worms that are capable of that transformation, and \softline
have bent our wills to be such.  As commentators have shown, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 antomata}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is Dante's version of \softline
Aristotle's creatures born, not of other creatures, but of the putrefaction of vegetable matter, as \softline
when the sun beats down on the mud -- see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 De generatione animalium}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.1, as cited by \softline
Benvenuto, comm. to vv. 124-129).  See also Aristotle's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Historia animalium}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.19, as cited by \softline
Pasquini/Quaglio (comm. to vv. 128-129), where Aristotle distinguishes, as Dante does here, \softline
between worms that can turn into butterflies and those, defective, which cannot.  The meaning \softline
clearly seems to be that we are born worms, but turn ourselves into still lesser beings, formally \softline
imperfect worms, as though we had not been bred by creatures with rational souls.  Benvenuto \softline
concludes by quoting Job (but actually the Psalms [21:7 (22:6)]): 'Vermis sum ego et non homo' \softline
(I am a worm, not a man).  He may have conflated that passage with Job 25:6.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 130-135.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   In a canto so concerned with art, and highly mimetic art in particular, it seems \softline
only natural that the poet would have wanted to conclude with a simile, one of this artisan's \softline
specialties.  We may be surprised to realize that this is the first one in this canto, that we have not \softline
seen one since well back in the last canto (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.34-42).  A corbel is a sculpted human figure, \softline
often crudely realistic, and thus part of the low-mimetic tradition, used to decorate the element \softline
that joins a weight-bearing column to the roof- or floor-beam that it supports.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The notion that an artifact can be so 'realistic' that, although it is not real, but a fiction, as 
it were, it can cause an observer real distress, continues the mimetic concern so evident in this \softline
canto and also stands as a sort of emblem of the poem as a whole, with its insistence on its literal \softline
truth dizzyingly countered by its less evident but clear admission that it is in fact invented by a \softline
poet, if one who will only write fictions that seem (and claim) to be utterly true.  For discussion of \softline
this passage in this light see Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Undivine "Comedy": Detheologizing Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: \softline
Princeton University Press, 1992]), pp. 125-26.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 136-137.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   We learn that, just as in hell there were sinners punished in differing degrees for \softline
the same sin, so in purging themselves penitents also reflect the degree of their former sinfulness.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 138.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   A small but continuing dispute in the commentaries debates whether }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 paz{\f3 \'56}enza}{\plain \fs24 \f1  should \softline
be interpreted as 'suffering' or 'patience.'  Philologically there is probably no advantage to either \softline
solution.  However, poetic logic points to a simple explanation (one shared by the vast majority of \softline
the commentators): what we face here is a relation of paradox rather than similarity.  Even the \softline
most stoical of the sinners seemed to be expressing the thought (another case of 'speech made \softline
visible') 'I can no more.'  Of course the one who suffered most would be saying such a thing; that \softline
would not be worth mentioning.  The point is that even the penitent least crushed by the weight of \softline
his former pride is suffering as much as one can possibly suffer.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Gerard Manley Hopkins offered, whether he wished to or not, a perfectly Dantean gloss to \softline
this verse.  In his 'terrible sonnet' named 'Carrion Comfort' by Robert Bridges, Hopkins, more \softline
likely citing Shakespeare's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Antony and Cleopatra}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (IV.xv.59) than Dante, has his speaking voice \softline
cry out, 'Not, I'll not... cry }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 I can no more}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  I can.'  While Antony says 'I can no more' and dies, \softline
Hopkins' persona does not give in to despair and continues to strive toward God.  Here, the \softline
penitents all seem to insist that they are at the end of their strength, yet all continue on the road \softline
toward making restitution to God by giving satisfaction for their sins and thus eventually obtain \softline
their final absolution.\par
